# Security Review: `app.js`

The file is a minimal Express.js application (23 lines). While it is small today, it contains several security gaps that will become serious liabilities as the application grows. Below are the findings, ranked by severity.

---

## 🔴 HIGH — Unauthenticated Data Exposure (OWASP A01 / A07)

**`/users` returns PII with no authentication or authorization.**

Any anonymous client can call `GET /users` and receive names and email addresses. This violates the principle of least privilege and likely violates GDPR/CCPA requirements.

```js
// ❌ Current — completely open
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }, ...]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Add an authentication middleware and, when real data is introduced, role-based access control.

```js
// ✅ Example using a JWT bearer-token middleware
const { expressjwt: jwt } = require('express-jwt');

const authenticate = jwt({
  secret: process.env.JWT_SECRET,  // never hard-code
  algorithms: ['HS256'],
});

app.get('/users', authenticate, (req, res) => {
  // Only reaches here if the token is valid
  res.json(users);
});
```

---

## 🔴 HIGH — Missing Security Headers (OWASP A05)

Express sets `X-Powered-By: Express` by default, advertising your stack to attackers. There are also no Content-Security-Policy, X-Frame-Options, HSTS, or other protective headers.

```js
// ✅ Add helmet — fixes ~14 header issues in one line
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

This disables `X-Powered-By`, sets `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, and more.

---

## 🟠 MEDIUM — No Rate Limiting (OWASP A04 / Denial of Service)

Both endpoints can be called unlimited times per second, enabling credential stuffing, enumeration attacks, and resource exhaustion.

```js
// ✅ Rate-limit all routes
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

app.use(limiter);
```

---

## 🟠 MEDIUM — No CORS Policy (OWASP A05)

There is no `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header. In a browser context this will either block all cross-origin requests (breaking legitimate clients) or — if misconfigured later — allow any origin to make credentialed requests.

```js
// ✅ Explicit allowlist
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'],
  methods: ['GET'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Authorization', 'Content-Type'],
}));
```

---

## 🟠 MEDIUM — No Global Error Handler (OWASP A09 / Information Disclosure)

Without a catch-all error handler, unhandled exceptions will send Express's default HTML error page, which may leak stack traces, file paths, or package versions to clients.

```js
// ✅ Add at the END of all route definitions (4-argument signature is required)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err);               // log full detail server-side only
  res.status(err.status ?? 500).json({
    error: 'An unexpected error occurred', // never send err.message or stack
  });
});
```

---

## 🟡 LOW — No Request Body Size Limit (OWASP A04)

The app doesn't currently parse request bodies, but when `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` is added (very likely), the default body size limit in older Express versions is 100 kb — and in some configurations is unlimited.

```js
